c489fcf5-df06-4ca4-807a-62c8349f4c72	FY27 Implementation Goals	1. Optimize and Stabilize the Data Delivery Process (DDP)\n  - Ramp and enable new team members\n  - Make DDP a fully supportable, self-sustaining capability\n  - Align with the AIM28 roadmap\n\n2. Advance Capacity Planning\n  - Build on standardized time capture across PSI and CSI\n  - Develop a robust capacity model\n  - Define and implement additional KPIs for workload, throughput, and performance\n\n3. Drive AI Adoption (AIM28)\n  - Identify and implement AI-enabled solutions per sub-team\n  - Expand agent usage and automation\n  - Track measurable outcomes such as efficiency gains and cost savings\n\n4. Proactively Manage Payer NCPDP Enhancements\n  - Plan for and execute significant upcoming NCPDP changes\n  - Balance slot scheduling with existing delivery commitments\n  - Emphasize cross‑functional planning and schedule discipline\n\n5. Standardize Risk Intelligence Capabilities\n  - Onboard and ramp new Risk Intelligence team members\n  - Standardize PIT and inherited FWA (Payer Investigations) processes\n  - Ensure consistency, scalability, and sustained effectiveness\n\n6. Optimize the Implementations Organization (Leaders Only)\n  - Define and document consistent job families and role expectations\n  - Optimize the Implementations org structure for long‑term scalability\n  - Standardize processes and procedures across all Implementation teams\n  - Transition the Copay team into a unified implementation model	manual	2026-04-15 18:23:40.386087+00	2026-04-27 15:30:07.421704+00	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
fc46ec2a-c08b-4bde-8240-cd81c30a967c	Payer Outcomes Update	Hey all,\n\nI wanted to provide an update on the Sierra payer outcomes calls pilot with ESI. Over the past month and a half, we've attempted more than 1,500 calls to assess the effectiveness of the process. We've been comparing Sierra's results to those our team achieved\nwhen calling the payer about the same PAs. Below is a summary of our findings.\n\nWe started the pilot with ESI, knowing we gain PA status 100% through their IVR, which means the bot never interacts with a human. After seeing positive results, we expanded to Tricare and Cigna, both under the EverNorth umbrella and using the same IVR system.\nWe tested 50 calls to each, following the same automated path, and only completed calls where the IVR provided status without any human interaction.\n\nOur success rate for these calls has consistently ranged between 93% and 98%. This means we're able to close PAs with a status and avoid routing them back to a team member for follow-up.\n\nThe accuracy rate stands at 85%, indicating that Sierra matches our team’s outcomes 85% of the time. In most other cases, Sierra was able to obtain outcomes that our team previously could not, demonstrating the bot's potential to outperform humans. Some mismatches\nwere due to human error or incorrect outcome marking. We are actively working to improve this number by ensuring Sierra has all necessary information, and we expect accuracy to rise as Sierra continues to outperform humans.\n\nOur next steps involve collaborating with the product group to build an integration for IVR-only plans. This will enable Sierra to handle all calls for these plans and automatically add outcomes to Hubble. We’ll continue monitoring performance through audits,\nreporting, and human-in-the-loop testing. To clarify, we are only automating calls that are entirely handled by IVR, with no human interaction at this stage.\n\nLooking ahead, we plan to explore whether Sierra can interact with human agents. For this to happen, Sierra will need to operate at the same or better pace than our current process. This will remain a focus as we move through the integration. I’d like to begin\ndiscussing what partnership will be needed from your teams to support this future state.\n\nIf you have any questions, please let me know.\n\nThank you!\n\nJosh\n\nJosh Campanella\n\nSr. Advisor, Contact Center Transformation	email	2026-04-11 20:25:33.848993+00	2026-04-11 20:25:33.848997+00	"Campanella, Josh" <Joshua.Campanella@covermymeds.com>	"Bednar, Sarah" <Sarah.Bednar@covermymeds.com>, "Leykam, Jordan" <jordan.leykam@covermymeds.com>, "Miller, Lindsay" <Lindsay.Miller@RelayHealth.com>, "Hieber, Bryan" <Bryan.Hieber@relayhealth.com>, "Dye, Brian" <brian.dye@mckesson.com>, "Scott, Shea" <Shea.Scott@covermymeds.com>	\N	\N	2026-04-08 15:27:32+00	<DS0PR02MB9222CD1F39C128BED1396DB2E35B2@DS0PR02MB9222.namprd02.prod.outlook.com>
98b95690-34e0-4f64-86d3-b8772fd34d16	Two major Lilly DC opportunities	Meeting Notes:\nIM from Tate:\nWe got two major lilly DC opptys and its got a short term manual component to it and wanna pick ur brain sooner than later \n\nRebound on DC\nBoth Lilly opportunities\nQuick Pin and Fandaho\nAdherence concept built into program\nPatient gets DC benefit, did they fill in 45 days\n  1. If so keep giving benefit, if not exclude them for no been if\n  2. If they fill 45 days, next lower copay \nDev work is need for both options - Dev is aware\n\nFirst option\n- Data science does looks backs, drop in folder currently today in COC\n- If we go with operation 1 we need to do the same for DC but Imp with do manual upload (pull the file)\n- If we were to say yes, nothing happens for 45 days but then a daily effort until code is deployed\n\nSecond option\n- All has to happen plus additional dc code\n___________________________________________________________________________________\n\n#AI Summarization (Markdown version)\n# Meeting Notes: Lilly DC Opportunities – Adherence Options\n\n## Overview\n- Two major **Lilly DC opportunities**\n- Both include a **short-term manual component**\n- Goal is to align quickly and evaluate options early\n\n## Key Topics Discussed\n- Rebound on DC  \n- Both Lilly opportunities  \n- Quick Pin / FoundaGo reference  \n- **Adherence concept** built into the program  \n\n## Adherence Concept\n- Patient receives DC benefit\n- Adherence check: **Did the patient fill within 45 days?**\n\n### Outcomes\n1. **Filled within 45 days**\n   - Continue DC benefit\n   - Apply **lower copay**\n2. **Did not fill within 45 days**\n   - Patient is **excluded from future benefit**\n\n- **Development work required for both options**\n- Dev team is already aware\n\n---\n\n## Option 1: Manual + Interim Operational Approach\n\n- **Data Science** performs historical lookbacks  \n- Output is **dropped into a folder** (current process lives in COC)\n- If this option is selected:\n  - Same approach must be implemented for **DC**\n  - **Implementations team** will manually pull and upload the file\n\n### Operational Impact\n- If approved:\n  - **No action for the first 45 days**\n  - After day 45, **daily manual effort** continues until code is deployed\n\n---\n\n## Option 2: Expanded Development (More Automated)\n\n- Includes **everything in Option 1**\n- Adds:\n  - **Additional DC-specific code**\n- Higher upfront dev effort, reduced ongoing manual work\n\n---\n\n## Open Considerations\n- Confirm preferred option (manual interim vs. expanded dev)\n- Align on development timelines\n- Validate tolerance for short-term manual processing post–45 days\n	manual	2026-04-13 17:59:43.002878+00	2026-04-13 18:00:22.27609+00	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
